issue.title: Authorization issue with ML pipeline having a Sweep job

issue.body:
SDK: V2
OS: Linux
Python: 3.10

We have an ML training pipeline with SDK V2 that uses a Sweep job. The pipelines use the environment that exists in a Shared ML Registry.

We are utilizing the command components for the training and Sweep jobs. All is well if there is no sweep job as we have tested with scoring and monitoring pipelines and with training pipelines if we remove the Sweep job. However, with a Sweep job in pipeline components, no child runs ever passes/completes. Each of the trials inside the child job has an error:
UserError: **This request is not authorized to perform this operation using this permission.**
![image](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-python/assets/17766651/d0e08eb2-1f65-4ada-878b-baf09fcb2f9c)

The overall job error says:
UserError: **This request is not authorized to perform this operation using this permission. Marking the experiment as failed because initial child jobs have failed due to user error**

![image](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-python/assets/17766651/8f2241ca-6bc5-4f00-9464-0db14239d04c)

Here is some psuedocode that can help:

```
try:
    logging.info('Getting latest environemnt from shared registry')
    matching_environments = [env for env in ml_client_registry.environments.list(e.aml_env_name_score) if any(e.target_env_tag in tag_value for tag_value in env.tags.values())]
    if matching_environments:
        pipeline_job_env = max(matching_environments, key=lambda env: env.version)
    else:
       raise Exception(f"No environment with {e.target_env_tag} tag found.")
except Exception as excp:
    logging.error('Unable to get latest environemnt from ML registry.')
    raise excp
```



```
@pipeline()
def sweden_backbook_train_with_hyperparameters(
    reg_targets,
    clf_targets,
    ml_datafile,
    preprocessing_config_file,
    port_agg_col,
    tgt_period_col,
    gpu_flag,
    dataset_deploy_flag,
    snapshot,
    deploy_flag,
    project_name,
    model_name,
    output_dir
):
    train_component = command(
	name="backbook-train",
	display_name="Training",
	description="Performs training and produces model",
	inputs={
		"reg_targets": Input(type='string'),
		...
		...
		...
		'reg_colsample_bylevel': Input(type='integer'),
		'reg_reg_alpha': Input(type='integer'),
		'reg_reg_lambda': Input(type='integer')
	},
	code=e.sources_directory,
	command="python -m train.main_portfolio",
	environment=pipeline_job_env,
    ).component(
	reg_targets=reg_targets,
	...,
	...
    )

    search_space = {
	...,
	...,
	'reg_colsample_bylevel': Uniform(min_value=0.3, max_value=1),
	'reg_reg_alpha': Choice([0, 0.01, 0.1, 0.5, 1, 10]),
	'reg_reg_lambda': Choice([0, 0.01, 0.1, 0.5, 1, 10]),
	'reg_tweedie_variance_power': Uniform(min_value=1.2, max_value=1.99),
	'zip_regressor': Choice(['Y','N'])
    }
    sweep_step = train_component.sweep(
	primary_metric="custom_mae_mean_cv",
	goal="minimize",
	sampling_algorithm='bayesian',
	search_space=search_space,
	compute=e.compute_name_train
    )
    sweep_step.set_limits(max_total_trials=int(e.max_total_trials), max_concurrent_trials=int(e.max_concurrent_trials), timeout=int(e.timeout))
```

We have reviewed all permissions on our end. We use a compute cluster for our pipelines. the cluster has a user-managed identity assigned and that identity has Manager rights on the shared registry. The pipeline works if there is no sweep job.

We believe it is a bug, can we please get some assistance with this?


**UPDATE:** (2023-10-11)

We have just realized that even though the environment linked to train component is in the shared ML registry but when the sweep runs, the individual trials have the linked environment in the workspace instead. The following image shows the trial and its linked environment:

![image](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-python/assets/17766651/d77d0c6f-4c66-4593-b433-ccd7ad08dba5)

And when clicked on environment, it takes us to the workspace environment, which couldn't build and hence the error in pipeline:
![image](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-python/assets/17766651/0ec4c45c-af34-4553-ab2b-6c28707efd8e)



This environment **gpu:Autosave_2023-10-10T18:31:27Z_a2ca7330** was not there in workspace environments prior to running the sweep job pipeline. **Is Sweep trying to build an environment in the workspace, even if the environment is already built in the shared registry**? Also, this doesn't happen with other pipeline or steps (that don't have sweep job), for example, here is environment details of another step in the same pipeline:
![image](https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-python/assets/17766651/31846fb0-6816-4f8d-a20b-d32763d663ae)

comment.body: Hi @edgBR  , when sweep over a command component (that using a registry environment), we have some system limitations that system needs to build an environment in workspace to support that. Could you please try to grant the missing permission to see if that can fix the issue? Sorry for the inconvenience. From our understanding, if customer see error in this case, it also means customer cannot submit a job with custom environment definition. We think when user submit a job, they should have such permissions.

issue.title: Logic Management Client workflow_runs.list operation mishandles `top` parameter
issue.body:
- **Package Name**: azure-mgmt-logic
- **Package Version**: 10.0.0 and 10.1.0b1
- **Operating System**: Ubuntu 22.04 on WSL2
- **Python Version**:  3.10.6

**Describe the bug**
 - In the current stable release (10.0.0): when passing an integer value to the `top` parameter in the LogicManagementClient.workflow_runs.list operation, e.g. `top = 10`, the desired number of results are returned, then value validation incorrectly fails, returning an error like the following: `(InvalidTopInQueryString) The value for top of '10,10' is not an integer; the value must be an integer value greater than zero.`. 

 - In the beta release (10.1.0b1): when passing an integer value to the `top` parameter in the LogicManagementClient.workflow_runs.list operation, the value for top is entirely ignored, returning more results than desired.

**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. 
```
workflow_runs = logic_client.workflow_runs.list(resource_group_name="my-rg", workflow_name="my-workflow", top = 10)
for i, run in enumerate(workflow_runs):
    print(i)
```
In the 10.0.0 package this prints numbers 0 through 9 but then the following error:
```
(InvalidTopInQueryString) The value for top of '10,10' is not an integer; the value must be an integer value greater than zero.\nCode: InvalidTopInQueryString\nMessage: The value for top of '10,10' is not an integer; the value must be an integer value greater than zero.\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"/home/user/test.py\", line 39, in run\n    for i, run in enumerate(workflow_runs):\n  File \"/home/user/.local/lib/python3.10/site-packages/azure/core/paging.py\", line 124, in __next__\n    return next(self._page_iterator)\n  File \"/home/user/.local/lib/python3.10/site-packages/azure/core/paging.py\", line 76, in __next__\n    self._response = self._get_next(self.continuation_token)\n  File \"/home/user/.local/lib/python3.10/site-packages/azure/mgmt/logic/operations/_workflow_runs_operations.py\", line 253, in get_next\n    raise HttpResponseError(response=response, model=error, error_format=ARMErrorFormat)\nazure.core.exceptions.HttpResponseError: (InvalidTopInQueryString) The value for top of '10,10' is not an integer; the value must be an integer value greater than zero.\nCode: InvalidTopInQueryString\nMessage: The value for top of '10,10' is not an integer; the value must be an integer value greater than zero.\n
```
With the 10.1.0b1 package this would prints the numbers 0 through 262 (the number of workflow runs I currently have), showing that the `top` parameter is ignored. 

**Expected behavior**
Passing integer X to the `top` parameter results in X workflow runs being returned in the response.

pull_request.title: [ML][Pipelines] feat: support v2 style environment override for flow component
pull_request.body:
# Description

1. support using aml environment in flow component
  1. works in `flow.dag.yaml` and `run.yaml`
  2. works on `--set` in cli and `params_override` in sdk
  3. works for registered workspace environment
```yaml
azureml:
  environment: azureml:xxx:x
```
registered registry environment
```yaml
azureml:
  environment: azureml://registries/xx/environments/xx/versions/x
```
nested environment
```yaml
azureml:
  environment:
    image: mcr.microsoft.com/azureml/openmpi4.1.0-ubuntu22.04
    conda_file:
      channels:
        - conda-forge
      dependencies:
        - python=3.9
        - pip:
          - azure-ai-ml
          - shrike
```
and standalone environment yaml
2. use normalized (replace '-' with '_' only for now) folder name as flow component name

pull_request.title: test what happens if change  to version-tolerant for Mgmt SDK generation
pull_request.body:
(1) file name change (may influence CLI):
- `_xxx_enum.py` -> `_enum.py`
- `_models_py3.py` -> `_models.py`
- `_xx_operation.py` -> `_operations.py`

(2) breaking change:
- client signature `credential`, `subscription_id` has different order
- client signature `base_url` is renamed to `endpoint`, and it is from positional to keyword-only
- all `header` and `query` method signature changes from positional to keyword-only

(3) other change:
- can't set `api_version` in operation
- no `case_insensitive_dict`
- no `_convert_request`
- no annotation for `cls` in docstring
- no `metadata` for operation
- [no `maxpagesize` for paging operation](https://github.com/Azure/autorest.python/blob/f3ed94c465cb988ea1432d193916ef2902a00ab0/packages/autorest.python/autorest/preprocess/__init__.py#L141):
